column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: LOADED FILLED IBC ON VAN TRAILER FOR DELIVERY. AFTER TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY THREE MILES THE IBC FAILED AND HEAVY LEAKAGE OCCURRED. THE TRANSPORT DRIVER NOTICED THE LEAKAGE OF PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER AFTER TRAVELING SEVERAL MILES. UPON INVESTIGATION DRIVER FOUND IBC TO BE EMPTY. THE CHARLOTTE/ MEEK. CO EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT OFFICE WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND APPROPRIATE CLEAN UP EFFORTS PERFORMED TO THE SATISFACTION OF MECKLENBURG CO. EPA. ONCE CONTAINER (IBC) WAS INSPECTED A CRACK TWO FEET LONG WAS OBSERVED IN THE BOTTOM OF THE IBC. THE MANUFACTURER OF THE IBC HAS BEEN NOTIFIED AND IS BEING RETURNED FOR THEM TO PERFORM TESTS TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE FOR THE FAILURE. THERE IS NO EXTERNAL DAMAGE TO THE IBC, THE IBC WAS PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED PER REGULATIONS. THE IBC WAS MANUFACTURED ON 9/96 AND WAS WITHIN TEST REQUIREMENTS. WE ARE HAVING OTHER IBC'S MANUFACTURED AT SAME TIME PERIOD TESTED AND INSPECTED.

ENROUTE TO NEW ORLEANS, LOUISIANA FROM PACE, FLORIDA, THE DRIVER NOTICED VAPORS COMING FROM THE TRAILER VENT AS THE VEHICLE SLOWED TO A STOP AT THE VEHICLE WEIGHT SCALES NEAR PENSACOLA, FLORIDA. THE DRIVER PARKED THE VEHICLE AND INSPECTED THE TRAILER AND FOUND THAT THE TRAILER MANUAL VENT VALVE HAD OPENED SLIGHTLY ABOUT 1/4 TURN. THE DRIVER TIGHTLY CLOSED THE VALVE AND ALL VENTING STOPPED. THE VEHICLE PROCEEDED ON TO NEW ORLEANS, LOUISIANA WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. CORRECTIVE ACTION: DRIVER MUST INSURE THAT THE VALVES ARE SECURELY CLOSED BEFORE DEPARTING/ LOADING/ UNLOADING ORIGIN AND DESTINATION LOCATIONS AND AT ALL SAFETY CHECKS.

column168: DURING SWITCHING ODOR WAS DETECTED NEAR RAPX 101. INSPECTION BY BNSF HAZMAT RESPONDER AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT REVEALED THAT ISOBUTANE WAS SPILLED INTO THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING DURING LOADING. AMBIENT TEMPERATURES WERE LOW ENOUGH TO KEEP THE PRODUCT IN IT'S LIQUID STATE. WHEN THE AMBIENT TEMPERATURE INCREASED THE ISOBUTANE BEGAN TO VAPORIZE CAUSING THE ODOR.

PASSENGERS COMPLAINED OF AN OBNOXIOUS ODOR IN THE CABIN OF THE AIRCRAFT AS IT WAS TAXING FROM THE CIT IN PREPARATION FOR DEPARTURE. CAPTAIN DAVE DELONG OPTED TO RETURN THE AIRCRAFT TO THE GATE SO THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR COULD BE PROPERLY INVESTIGATED. SEVERAL PASSENGERS STATED THE ODOR AS WELL AS THE PHYSICAL REACTION WERE SIMILAR TO THAT OF MACE OR PEPPER SPRAY. ONCE THE AIRCRAFT HAD RETURNED TO GATE 2 AT THE HHH TERMINAL IN MSP, IT WAS MEET BY SUN COUNTRY AIRLINES CUSTOMER SERVICE AGENTS AND MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL. MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL WANTED TO INSPECT THE AIRCRAFT TO ENSURE THE AIRCRAFT WAS SAFE FOR FLIGHT, SO THE PASSENGERS WERE REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT. THE PASSENGERS WERE REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND ESCORTED OUT OF THE STERILE AREA AND SCREENED ONCE AGAIN, IN THE HOPES OF DISCOVERING A PASSENGER WITH MACE OR PEPPER SPRAY. THE AIRCRAFT WAS THOROUGHLY SEARCH BY CREW MEMBERS, AND A MACE CONTAINER WAS FOUND ON THE FLOOR OF THE AIRCRAFT NEAR SEAT NUMBER 20F. UPON REBOARDING OF THE PASSENGER, ALL PASSENGERS SEATED NEAR 20F WERE BY AN SEVERAL INDIVIDUALS FROM THE FAA, AS WELL AS OFFICER PETERSON OF THE MSP AIRPORT POLICE. THE INTERVIEW PROCESS WAS NEGATIVE. THE AIRCRAFT DEPARTED APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS LATE.

column168: MIKE ARRIVED TO THE TERMINAL, HOOKED UP TO HIS UNIT AND HE DID HIS UNIT PRE-TRIP INSPECTION. HE WENT TO OLIN AND LOADED. AFTER LOADING HE SECURED HIS DOME LID AND PROCEEDED ONTO THE SCALES. AFTER SCALING HE PULLED UP TO THEIR GATE TO DEPART AND NOTICED ACID GOING DOWN THE SIDES OF HIS TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY GOT OUT TO DISCOVER THAT THE TRAILER WASH OUT CAPS WERE MISSING. HE CALLED TO REPORT THAT APPROXIMATELY 5 TO 10 GALLONS OF ACID WAS ON THE PARKING LOT. WE DISPATCHED A CREW OUT THERE WITH SODA ASH AND WERE GOING TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN UP. UPON ARRIVAL OLIN PERSONNEL STARTED THE CLEAN UP AND TOLD US THAT THEY HAD IT UNDER CONTROL. I HAVE CHECKED INTO THE ACTIONS OF THE CLEANING TECHNICIAN, WHO CLEANED THE TRAILER AND HE DID NOT REPLACE THE WASH OUT CAPS AS HE SHOULD HAVE. MIKE DID NOT THOROUGHLY CONDUCT A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION. WE ARE HAVING MEETINGS WITH THE WASH RACK PERSONNEL AND ALSO WITH DRIVERS TO ASSURE IN THE FUTURE THAT ALL PERSONS DO THEIR JOBS THOROUGHLY TO AVOID SITUATIONS OF THIS NATURE FROM RECURRING.

TANK WAS PRESSURIZED FOR AIR UNLOADING.  THE INTERNAL SAFETY VALVE WAS FROZEN CLOSED DUE TO COLD TEMPERATURE OUTSIDE AND NATURE OF PRODUCT.  TANK WAS MOVED TO ANOTHER LOCATION IN THE PLANT TO APPLY STEAM TO THE VALVE.  ONCE HEATED, THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS OPENED AND CLOSED.  THIS ALLOWED TANK PRESSURE TO ENTER THE UNLOADING LINE TO THE EXTERNAL VALVE.  THE EXTERNAL VALVE WAS EITHER (1) OPEN TO A SLIGHT DEGREE OR,(2) OBSTRUCTED BY FROZEN, SOLIDIFIED PRODUCT.  AFTER TANK WAS LOCATED BACK TO THE UNLOADING PAD, AND IN PROCESS OF REMOVING THE OUTLET CAP, PRODUCT ESCAPED ( UNDER PRESSURE)  AND SPRAYED REAR OF TRAILER.  DRIVER WAS IN FULL PROTECTIVE SUIT BUT RECEIVED A MINOR BURN ON CHIN. IN ALL CASES THIS EVENT COULD (AND WILL ) BE AVOIDED BY FIRST DE-PRESSURIZING THE TANK.

DRUM WAS BEING FILLED WITH 2 GAL CONTAINER AND LIQUID DRAINED OUT DEFECTIVE WELD IN BOTTOM.  FAILURE WAS NOTICED IMMEDIATELY  AND FILLING STOPPED. VERMICULITE AND ABSORBANT PADS WERE IMMEDIATELY APPLIED TO SPILL TO ABSORB SPILL. ABSORBANT WAS SWEPT INTO WASTE CONTAINER FOR ULTIMATE DISPOSAL.  ALL CONTACTED AREAS WERE PADDED WITH ABSORBANT TO COLLECT EVERY EVIDENCE OF FREE LIQUIDS.  NO INJURIES OR OFF SITE MIGRATION OF WASTE WAS DETECTED.

WHILE MOVING A SKID, LEAKAGE WAS DISCOVERED.  UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS FOUND TO BE CAUSED BY HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP. ALL CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM AND THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED.

ON THE MORNING OF 03/28 A PRIVATE CONTRACTOR WENT TO GAUGE THE CAR. THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM AROUND THE SAFETY REFIEF VALVE. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED & THEY RESPONDED. CSXT RESPONDED A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER. A LOCAL CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO CONDUCT AIR MONITORING WITH A COMBUSTIBLE GAS METER. EMPTY TANKER TRUCKS WERE CALLED TO OFF LOAD SOME OF THE PRODUCT AND A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR OUT OF NASHVILLE, TN.  RESPONDED TO OVERSEE THE TRANSLOADING OPERATION. APPROXIMATELY 5,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OFF THE TANK CAR. AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THE CAR WILL BE BILLED BACK TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY TO BE INSPECTED.

column168: THE CARGO TANK, CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS OF 15% HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION, WAS PARKED ON THE DISTRICT FACILITY YARD IN FAIRMOUNT CITY.  AN EMPLOYEE NOTICED A SMALL LEAK AT VICTAULIC COUPLING ON THE MANIFOLD UNDER THE TANK. APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS HAD LEAKED OUT AT THE TIME THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA AND PLACED INTO PLASTIC WASTE DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  BOTTOM DISCHARGE VALVES AND MANIFOLD COUPLINGS ON THE CARGO TANK HAVE BEEN REPLACED.

THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT AND LOADED ON AN AIRCRAFT AND WAS IN FLIGHT/ ENROUTE WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED. THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN PART OF A FREIGHT LOAD CONSIGNED AND LOADED ON FEDEX FEEDER FLIGHT 8315 (MEM-BWG), MEMPHIS, TENNESSEE-BOWLING GREEN, KENTUCKY. THE AIRCRAFT LOST ALTITUDE AND CRASHED IN THE CLARKSVILLE, TENNESSEE AREA WHICH WAS ABOUT 40 MILES SOUTHWEST OF BOWLING GREEN, KENTUCKY WHICH WAS THE FINAL DESTINATION FOR THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE SITE BY LOCAL AUTHORITIES. THE SHIPMENT'S PAPER WORK SHOWED NOT ONLY THE XYLENES BUT SEVERAL OTHER PROPER SHIPPING NAMES INCLUDING THE FOLLOWING: PRINTING INK- UN1210, ADHESIVES-UN1133, RESIN SOLUTION-UN1866. THERE WERE ACTUALLY ONLY THREE PIECES OF FLAMMABLES ON BOARD THE AIRCRAFT. THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT TRAVELED BY GROUND TO IT'S DESTINATION.

column168: DRIVER STOPPED AT A TRUCK STOP ENROUTE FOR TIRE AND EQUIPMENT CHECK AND DISCOVERED THE TRAILER TO DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE EXTERNAL VALVE ON THE PRODUCT UNLOADING LINE. DRIVER PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE LEAK AND SUMMONED ASSISTANCE. CARRIER SENT 1 TRAINED TECHNICIAN LEVEL RESPONDER AND THE DRIP WAS STOPPED BY ADJUSTING THE PACKING ON THE EXTERNAL VALVE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAY.

DRIVER WAS UTILIZING THE CUSTOMER'S UNLOADING FITTING TO CONNECT THE TANK TRUCK DELIVERY HOSE THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE SYSTEM. DRIVER FAILED TO CHECK THE GASKETS IN THE CUSTOMER'S CONNECTIONS PRIOR TO ACTUALLY CONNECTING THEM. ONE OF THE GASKETS WAS NOT SEATED PROPERLY AND CAUSED A SMALL STREAM OF PRODUCT TO SPRAY OUT OF THE CONNECTION WHEN THE PRODUCT STARTED TO MOVE THROUGH THE UNLOADING LINE. MATERIAL LEAKED ONTO DRIVER'S PROTECTIVE TROUSERS AND ONTO THE GROUND. CUSTOMER PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT. NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAYS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: DRIVER STOPPED FOR THE 4TH TIRE CHECK OF TRIP SINCE LEAVING THE SHIPPER'S PLANT, AND NOTED THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING AT BOTTOM FROM OUTER JACKET. DRIVER SUMMONED HELP. MISSISSIPPI STATE POLICE, MISSISSIPPI PUBLIC SERVICE COMMISSION RESPONDED. THEY CONFERRED WITH MISSISSIPPI HAZMAT BY PHONE. DRIVER HAD THE SMALL DRIP LEAK CAPTURED IN A DRUM. CARRIER SENT 2 TRAINED EMERGENCY RESPONSE TECHNICIAN LEVEL PERSONS TO TRANSFER LOAD FROM TRAILER 6986 TO 7681. SHIPPER (DU PONT) SENT 4 EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL TO SCENE (TERP TEAM). SHIPPER TEAM CLEANED UP SPILLED MATERIAL. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO KNOWN PRODUCT REACHING ANY WATERWAY.

ONE 55 GALLON DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY TURNED OVER TO STOP THE LEAKAGE. APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS HAD LEAKED OUT INTO THE TRAILER. OIL DRY WAS PLACED ON TOP OF THE SPILLED LIQUID TO ABSORB IT. THE DRUM WAS HELD AT MEMPHIS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL AND THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEANED UP BY PICKING UP THE OIL DRY. THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS DISCIPLINED. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THE MSDS SHEETS OBTAINED.
METAL PLATE ON REAR OF TRAILER WAS BENT UP AND WHEN DOCKMAN WAS UNLOADING, THE METAL PCS STICKING UP PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF PLASTIC DRUM.
DRIVER WAS TOLD THERE WAS ENOUGH ROOM FOR THE LOAD, BUT ALL OF THE LOAD COULD NOT FIT CAUSING SPILL. SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP BY CUSTOMER.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT CONSIGNEE AND WEIGH IN. SECURITY GUARD SAID HE WOULD HAVE TO WAIT FOR 1 HOUR TO GET UNLOADED AND TO PARK IN THE HOLDING AREA. HE PARKED UNIT AND NOTICED A SLIGHT RELEASE OF VAPOR AT TOP REAR OF CARGO TANK BOX. HE DONNED HIS PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT(RUBBER SUIT, HARD HAT, GOGGLES, RESPIRATOR AND FACE SHIELD) AND WENT ON TOP TO CHECK. HE DISCOVERED VAPOR HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM VAPOR LINE. HE TIGHTENED CAP, WHICH SLOWED VAPOR. HE NOTIFIED SAFETY AND SHIPPER. HE SHUT OFF HEAT TO VALVES AND VAPOR AND FOUND THAT GASKET WAS MISSING ON VAPOR LINE CAP.
DRIVER UNLOADING AND THE HOSE BURST OPEN. CUSTOMER CLEANED UP SPILL.
DRIVER BEGAN UNLOADING AND HOSE FITTING BEGAN TO LEAK. DRIVER CHANGED GASKET AND CORRECTED PROBLEM. USED ABSORBENTS TO CLEAN UP.

DRIVER HOOKED UNLOADING HOSE TO CUSTOMER'S LINE AND THE CUSTOMER EMPLOYEE DID NOT OPEN THE PLANT VALVE. WHEN PRODUCT BEGAN TO FLOW,  A GASKET IN THE CUSTOMER'S LINE BLEW OUT AND SPRAYED PRODUCT ONTO FLOOR OF PLANT. CUSTOMER PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, AND NO MATERIAL REACHED ANY WATERWAY.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1010 HOURS ON THURSDAY, MARCH 12, 1998, CONRAIL TRAIN WANF-90 ENTERED ONTO THE PROPERTY OF VANDEMARK COMPANY IN NIAGARA FALLS, NY TO PERFORM SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  AN EMPLOYEE OF VANDEMARK ACCOMPANIED THE CONDUCTOR, REMOVED THE BLUE FLAG PROTECTION AND INDICATED THAT THE CARS TO BE SWITCHED FROM THE PLANT WERE READY TO BE MOVED. AS THE WANF-90 BEGAN PULLING THE RAIL CARS TO BE SWITCHED, THE CONDUCTOR OBSERVED THAT A  HOSE HAD BECOME DISENGAGED AND WAS RELEASING PRODUCT (CHLORINE). THE CONDUCTOR ORDERED THE SWITCHING MOVE TO STOP AND ALSO ADVISED THE ENGINEER OF THE RELEASE AND TO PREPARE TO PROCEED UPWIND. AS THE CARS WERE BEING SWITCHED, TANK CAR ACFX240079 (RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINED CHLORINE) HAD NOT HAD THE PRODUCT UNL0ADING HOSES REMOVED FORM THE TANK CARE VALVES.  AS THE TANK CAR WAS PULLED THE HOSE PLACED TRESS ON THE LOADING RACK AND CAUSED A SECOND UNLOADING HOSE CONNED TO TANK CAR SBLX14031 (CHLORINE) ON AN ADJACENT TRACK TO DISLODGE FROM ITS CONNECTION POINT ON THE LOADING RACK. APPROXIMATELY 66 POUNDS OF CHLORINE ESCAPED FROM THE UNLOADING HOSE BEFORE EXCESS FLOW CHECK VALVES ACTIVATED AND STEMMED THE RELEASE OF ADDITIONAL PRODUCT. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE INCLUDING CHEMTREC AND THE REGIONAL CLOREP TEAM. THE INCIDENT COMMANDER ORDERED THAT THE RESIDENTS OF SEVERAL NEARBY HOMES AND AN ELEMENTARY SCHOOL SHELTER IN PLACE DURING THE EMERGENCY.  THE ELEMENTARY SCHOOL OFFICIALS, UNCERTAIN AS TO THE LENGTH OF THE SHELTER IN PLACE ORDER, OPTED TO BUS THE STUDENTS TO THE LOCAL HIGH SCHOOL WERE THEY WERE GIVEN AN EARLY DISMISSAL.

AS THE DRIVER WAS LEAVING LEASE, HE STOPPED ON CATTLE GUARD AT THE END OF THE LEASE ROAD TO CHECK FOR ONCOMING TRAFFIC.  THE DRIVER WAS NOT NOTIFIED BY LEASE PUMPER THAT THE GATED WAS DEFECTIVE; VARIATIONS FROM THE TRUCK ENGINE CAUSED THE GATE TO CLOSE SUDDENLY PUNCTURING A HOLE IN THE CARGO TANK.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE OKLAHOMA CORPORATION COMMISSION AND THE LEASE PUMP CALLED FOR CLEANUP. CORRECTIVE ACTIONS: DRIVER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO CHECK WITH LEASE PERSONNEL FOR FAULTY EQUIPMENT AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS.

ON MARCH 26, 1998 AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00 P.M.M A TRACTOR, SEMI TRAILER WITH A PUP HAD JUST COMPLETED LOADING THE CHEVRON USA SULFUR LOADING TERMINAL AT GLENCO. THE UNIT HAD PROCEEDED TO THE SCALE TO WEIGH AND THE TRACTOR HAD PULLED UNTO THE SCALE WHEN THE SCALE MALFUNCTIONED.  THE DRIVER WAS FORCED TO ATTEMPT TO BACK THE UNIT OFF OF THE SCALE (EVEN THOUGH BACKING THIS UNIT IS NEARLY IMPOSSIBLE) TO ALLOW IT TO RESET ITSELF. AS THE UNITY WAS BACKING THE PUP VEERED TO THE RIGHT AND THE DRIVER WAS FORCED TO STOP. THE APPROACH TO THE SCALE IS BUILT ON THE SIDE OF A HILL, AND THE PUP STOPPED NEAR THE EDGE.  ALMOST IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE UNIT CAME T O A STOP, THE WHEELS OF THE PUP CLOSEST TO THE EDGE (RIGHT SIDE) BEGAN SINKING INTO THE ROAD BED.  THE EDGE CAVED OFF AND THE PUP BEGAN TO SLIDE DOWN HILL.  THE PUP SILD DOWN THE HILL WITH ONLY THE LONGUE TO STOP IT FORM GOING TO THE BOTTOM. THE TANKS USED TO HAUL THIS PRODUCT CAN NOT WITHSTAND THE STRESS CAUSED WHEN TRYING TO UP RIGHT THEM WHILE LOADED.  THE DRIVER, AS INSTRUCTED, OPENED THE LOADING HATCH AND THE CONTENTS (9 TON) FLOWED OUT OF THE TANK.  THE CONTENTS CONTINUED DOWN INTO A DRAINAGE DITCH AT THE BOTTOM OF THE HILL.  THE PRODUCT IMMEDIATELY BEGAN TO COOL AND HARDEN INTO A SOLID.  THERE IS A CULVERT  THAT ALLOWS WATER FROM THE DITCH TO FLOW UNDER THE MAIN ROAD, THE CULVERT FILLED WITH SULFUR BUT DID NOT EXIT THE FAR END AS IT SETUP INSIDE BEFORE REACHING THAT POINT.  THERE WAS NO CONTACT WITH GROUND WATER OR SOIL CONTAMINATION. THE CONSTRUCTION COMPANY HIRED BEGAN THEIR CLEANUP AND REPLACEMENT OF THE CULVERT UNDER THE ROAD.  THE OLD CULVERT WAS EMPTIED OF THE SULFUR AND WILL BE SCRAPPED.  THE AREA WERE THE SULFUR POOLED AND SETUP HAS BEEN CLEANED AND AT THIS POINT WE ARE WAITING FOR THE WEATHER TO HOLD, ALLOWING US TO TRANSPORT THE REMAINING SALVAGE TO ROCK SPRINGS AND S F PHOSPHATE LTD.  (S F PHOS., IS THE PURCHASER OF THE PRODUCT F.O.B. GLENCO).  COMPLETE RECLAMATION SHOULD BE ACCOMPLISHED WITHIN THE NEXT FEW WEEKS, WEATHER PERMITTING.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT 0635, MARCH 27, 1998, A SEMI TRUCK DROVE INTO THE SIDE OF CANADIAN PACIFIC RAILWAY TRAIN NO. 429-26, DERAILING 13 CARS THAT INCLUDED GATX 10017, A TANK CARLOAD OF FLUOROSILICIC ACID, CORROSIVE MATERIAL, THE TANK CAR ROLLED ONTO ITS TOP DAMAGING 3 OF THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPILL FROM THE MANWAY INTO A DRAINAGE DITCH. APPROXIMATELY 12,000 GALLONS WERE SPILLED CONTAMINATING THE SURROUNDING WATER AND SOIL. THE DRIVER OF THE SEMI TRUCK WAS KILLED ON IMPACT. THE SEMI DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON HIGHWAY 32, DURING FOGGY CONDITIONS AND HE APPARENTLY DID NOT SEE THE TRAIN UNTIL JUST BEFORE IMPACT. SERVICE RESPONSE AND REMEDIATION INC., OUT OF MINNEAPOLIS, MN., WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE BY THE CANADIAN PACIFIC RAILWAY, TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID AND CLEAN UP THE CONTAMINATED SOILS. CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED ON APRIL 3, 1998.

THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

MANWAY COVER GASKET PINCHED AND MISSING APPROXIMATELY 35%, PLCX 224620, MARCH, 1998, PHILADELPHIA DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1100 HOURS, THURSDAY, MARCH 12, 1998, THE CONSIGNEE REPORTED PRODUCT ON THE SIDE OF TANK CAR PLCX 2246200 CONTAINING ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES, LIQUID, NOS.  APPROPRIATE MADE. CONRAIL'S TERMINAL GENERAL FOREMAN ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS PINCHED AND MISSING APPROXIMATELY 35% OF SAME.  REPAIRS WERE MADE BY GATX WHO REPLACED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET.  CLEAN HARBOR  CLEANED CAR, CONTAINED RUNOFF AND PLACED MATERIAL IN RECOVERY DRUMS.  THERE WAS NO REPORT ON THE GROUND. THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

column42: PROPIONIC ACID WITH NOT LESS THAN 10% AND LESS THAN 90% ACID BY MASS
column168: IMPROPERLY APPLIED MANWAY COVER GASKET, UTLX 86931, MARCH 13, 1998, INDIANAPOLIS DIVISION. AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 HOURS, FRIDAY, MARCH 13, 1998, AT CONRAIL'S DICKINSON YARD IN BELLE, WV, A CONRAIL YARD CREW NOTED PRODUCT ON TOP AND SIDE OF TANK CAR UTLX 86931 CONTAINING PROPIONIC ACID.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1644 HOURS, THE UNION CARBIDE HELP TEAM ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS NOT SEATED ON THE MANWAY NOZZLE CORRECTLY THEREBY ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK.  REPAIRS WERE MADE BY THE UNION CARBIDE HELP TEAM WHO PROPERLY APPLIED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET.  THERE WAS NO REPORT OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1700 HOURS, MARCH 13. 1998, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

TRAILER WAS PRESSURIZED FOR UNLOADING.  SHORTLY AFTER PRESSURIZATION, THE LARGE MAN-WAY ASSEMBLY (COLLER) CAME PARTIALLY SEPARATED FROM THE TOP OF THE TRAILER BODY. THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAY.  FURTHER INSPECTION OF VEHICLE FOUND THAT METAL FATIGUE WAS THE APPARENT PROBLEM. CORROSION DID NOT SEEM TO HAVE PLAYED A PART IN THIS INCIDENT.  INSPECTION FOUND THE RUBBER COATING ON THE INTERIOR AND EXTERIOR OF THE TRAILER BARREL TO BE IN APPARENT GOOD SHAPE.

DRIVER FAILED TO CHECK TIGHTNESS OF DOME COVER AFTER TRAILER WAS LOADED SHIPPER PERSONNEL.  HE PROCEEDED TO OPERATE THE TRAILER ON HIGHWAY AND WHEN HE PULLED INTO THE OHIO STATE SCALE AT BOLIVAR, OHIO.  THE AUTHORITIES NOTICED THE TRAILER LEAKING DOME LID LEAKING PRODUCT.  TRUCK WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE UNTIL ERROR CORRECTED AND SPILLED PRODUCT CLEANED UP ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP VENDOR HIRED TO CLEAN UP.  DRIVER WAS ISSUED A CITATION BY THE OHIO AUTHORITIES.  THERE WERE NO KNOWN INJURIES, AND THERE WAS NO KNOWN EXPOSURE TO ANY WATERWAY.

WE CALLED THE MANUFACTURE EMERGENCY NUMBER LISTED ON THE BILL OF LADING, THEY IN TURN CALLED CHEMTREC WHO FAXED A DETAILED MSDS SHEET, CHEMTREC NOTIFIED SUPERIOR SERVICES TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. WE THEORIZE THAT THE INCIDENT WA CAUSED EITHER BY A POOR HOLD ON THE DRUM OR WHEN THE FORKLIFT'S TIRES HIT THE DOCK PLATE IT CAUSED ENOUGH MOVEMENT FOR THE DRUM TO UNHOOK.  MATER HANDLERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED NOT TO RAISE THE DRUM TOO FAR FROM THE FLOOR AND TO PROCEED VERY SLOWLY OVER DOCK PLATER.

column168: DERAILMENT, MARCH 20, 1998, PITTSBURGH DIVISION.  CONRAIL TRAIN TOPI0 DERAILED TWENTY-TWO (22) CARS AT MILEPOST 36.6 ON THE FORT WAYNE LINE IN BIG BEAVER, PA. PROVIDED IS A LIST OF ELEVEN (11) TANK CARS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT.  TANK CAR NATX 37826 RESIDUE METHANOL LOST A NEGLIGIBLE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WHEN ITS BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE SHEARED OFF AT ITS MOUNTING TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET EXTERNAL BALL VALVE. THE CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A SKID AND IT APPEARED THE BOTTOM OF THIS EXTERNAL BALL VALVE HAD SLID ACROSS AN OBJECT.  A SLIGHT VAPOR LEAK WAS NOTED AT THE BALL VALVE POSSIBLY DUE TO THE IMPACT PARTIALLY UNSEATING THE VALVE AS THE HANDLE INDICATED THE VALVE WAS FULLY CLOSED.  REPAIRS WERE MADE BY CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER. "PLUG-N-DIKE" WAS PLACED OVER THE BALL VALVE BUT THE LEAK PERSISTED. THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE WAS REATTACHED USING "C" CLAMPS WITH A PIECE OF RUBBER BETWEEN IT AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0130 HOURS, MARCH 21, 1998, THE LEAK CEASED.  ALSO, TANK CAR MBLX 3732 SUSTAINED TANK DAMAGE AND WAS FORWARDED TO ENON VALLEY PA FOR TRANSFER. THE TANK CAR WAS CLEANED AND PURGED BY OHM REMEDIATION AND WILL BE SCRAPPED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0400 HOURS, THE BIG BEAVER, PA VFD CHIEF CALLED THE LOCAL EVACUATION OFF ALLOWING 15 FAMILIES TO RETURN TO THEIR HOME. THE MAJORITY OF THE DAMAGE TO CARS MBLX 34845, MBLX 34314, MBLX 34851, MBLX 34019, MBLX  34015 AND GATX 61643 WAS CENTERED ABOUT ITS DRAFT SILL, AIR BRAKE EQUIPMENT AND SAFETY APPLIANCES.  MBLX 34316 HAD ALL WHEELS OF THE TRACK BUT WAS UPRIGHT IN LINE AND MBLX 34028 HAD ITS "B" END TRUCK DERAILED AND IT WAS UPRIGHT LINE.  GATX 61551 HAD 2 SMALL GOUGES ON THE TANK LESS THAN 1/16" INCH DEEP AT ITS BOTTOM APPROXIMATELY 15 FEET FROM ITS "B" STUB SILL.  CAR HAD ROLLED APPROXIMATELY 150 DEGREES TO ITS "L" SIDE, WAS PERPENDICULAR TO THE TRACKS AND THE "A" END SILL WAS SPLIT OPEN.  THE JACKET WAS TORN AT MIDTANK.  MBLX 34236 HAD A GOUGE APPROXIMATELY 24 INCHES LONG (LONGITUDINAL TO THE TANK)  RUNNING APPROXIMATELY 8 FEET FROM ITS "B" SIDE BODY BOLSTER TO 10 FEET FROM THE "BL" BODY BOLSTER.  THE DEPTH OF THE GOUGE WAS NOTED TO BE A 9/32" USING A TIRE DEPTH GAUGE AT ITS CENTER.  ALL CAR WITH EXCEPTIONS OF MBLX 34236 WERE TO BE RERAILED AND TRANSPORTED TO CONWAY, PA FOR TRANSFER AND REPAIR AS REQUIRED.  MBLX 34236 WAS FORWARDED WEST TO ENON VALLEY, PA FOR TRANSFER.  THE TRANSFER AT THIS LOCALE WAS DUE TO THE CONDITION OF ITS SAFETY APPLIANCES, AIR BRAKE EQUIPMENT AND DRAFT SILL.  ON MARCH 26, 1998, TRANSFER CLEAN UP PURGE OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETED.  MOBIL OIL CO, PAULSBORO, NJ HAD DISPATCHED OHM REMEDIATION SERVICES CORPORATION, FINDLAY, OH PERSONNEL TO EFFECT THE TRANSFER OF ALL THE TANK CARS IN LPG SERVICE. THE CRATE OF METAL PRODUCT DID NOT APPEAR TO BE CONTAMINATED (IT WAS STACKED ON TOP OF THE METAL ROUND STOCK).  THE BOTTOM BOARDS OF THE PALLET THAT HAD THE MACHINE WERE REMOVED AND DRUMMED. column168: ON SATURDAY, MARCH 28, 1998 AT 1330 PM OUR TRANSPORT DRIVER, MARVIN IVY WAS INVOLVED IN A ONE-VEHICLE ACCIDENT RESULTING IN A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RELEASE. MR. IVY LOADED 7,001 GROSS (6,923) NET GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL AT THE DIAMOND SHAMROCK, HARLINGEN TERMINAL IN HARLINGEN TEXAS. WHILE NAVIGATING A SHARP CURVE AT THE INTERSECTION OF FM 508 AND FM 1420 IN RIO HONDO, TEXAS THE UNIT BEGAN TO SKID, TRAVELING OFF THE ROADWAY, ROLLED THREE-QUARTERS OF A TURN AND CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE IN A CROP FIELD APPROXIMATELY 36 FEET FROM THE ROAD. DAMAGE TO THE RIGHT SIDE AND TOP OF THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS SUSTAINED. CODE 3, INC., ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL BY CAMERON COUNTY SHERIFF'S DISPATCH AND TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY. BOTH OFFICIALS REQUESTED THAT CODE 3, INC. RESPOND AND MITIGATE THE INCIDENT. UPON ARRIVAL CODE 3, INC. FOUND DIESEL FUEL BEING RELEASED FROM THE DOME LID ON THE TRAILER AND SMALLER LOCATIONS AS WELL. CODE 3, CONTACTED OUR ORGANIZATION, THE DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY AND THE TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCE CONSERVATION COMMISSION. SIMONS PETROLEUM DISPATCHED A TRUCK TO THE AREA TO ASSIST WITH THE FUEL RECOVERY EFFORTS. HOLES WERE DRILLED INTO EACH COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER ABOVE THE PRODUCT LEVEL TO PREVENT FURTHER FUEL FROM BEING RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE RIO HONDO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON STAND-BY WITH FIRE SUPPRESSION EQUIPMENT DURING THE TRAILER DRILLING OPERATION. THE OVERTURNED TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE UPRIGHTED USING AIR BAGS AND A WRECKER/WINCH TRUCK. LAFERIA WRECKER SERVICE TOOK THE ENTIRE UNIT TO THEIR YARD IN LAFERIA, TEXAS. OUR EMPLOYEE/DRIVER, MARVIN IVY WAS TRANSPORTED IMMEDIATELY BY AMBULANCE TO VALLEY BAPTIST MEDICAL CENTER WHERE HE WAS TREATED FOR MINOR INJURIES AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY. CODE 3, INC. STARTED THE IMMEDIATE EXCAVATION OF CONTAMINATED SOIL ON SUNDAY, MARCH 29. OVER-EXCAVATION OF THE AREA WAS DONE(70 FT. X 20 FT. X 5 FT. DEEP) TO MITIGATE THE CONDITIONS AT THE SITE. AT A DEPTH OF 5 FEET, GROUND WATER WAS ENCOUNTERED DUE TO SHALLOW AQUIFER COMMON IN THIS AREA OF THE VALLEY. A FRENCH DRAIN SYSTEM WAS INSTALLED TO RECOVER THE DIESEL FUEL THAT MIGRATED TO THE TOP. ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS TRANSPORTED TO ALVAREZ TRUCKING, LOCATED 3.2 MILES WEST FROM THE SITE ON FM 508. A BERM WAS CONSTRUCTED AND LINED WITH PLASTIC FOR THE CONTAMINATED SOIL TO BE PLACED ON, THEN COVERED WITH PLASTIC TO PREVENT ANY RUNOFF DURING A RAINFALL EVENT FROM CONTAMINATING THE PROPERTY. SOIL SAMPLES WERE COLLECTED FOR TPH LEVELS. MICROBES WERE SPRAYED ON THE EXCAVATION SITE AND A SAFETY FENCE WAS INSTALLED AROUND THE AREA. REPLACEMENT SOIL WAS SOUGHT AT VARIOUS SOURCES DUE TO THE REQUIREMENTS OF THE LANDOWNER AND HIS CONCERNS WITH REPLACEMENT SOIL CONTAMINATED WITH HERBICIDES. REPLACEMENT SOIL WAS TESTED PRIOR TO BACKFILL OPERATIONS. DISPOSAL OF THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS COORDINATED THROUGH CODE 3, INC. ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES. A TOTAL OF 341 CUBIC YARDS OF CLASS I HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS TAKEN TO

CONSULTED DECISION TREE. IDENTIFIED AS A CORROSIVE HAZARD. CONSULTED PROPER RESPONSE SHEET. TESTED PH. APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE. PUT PACKAGE INTO DMP SPILL TRAY. AND PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.

column168: PHONE CALL RECEIVED AT 03:47 AM FROM ALEX CHAMBERS DESCRIBING LEAKING PRODUCT FROM TRAILER NEAR PEACE BRIDGE BORDER CROSSING FROM BUFFALO INTO CANADA.  DRIVER WAS CONFERENCED WITH ME, WHEREBY HE EXPLAINED HE BENT UNDER BACK OF TRAILER TO GET A BETTER LOOK BUT LIQUID DRIPPED NEAR HIS EYE.  i ASKED IF HE HAD HIS BILL OF LADING AND HE RESPONDED IT WAS ON THE SEAT OF HIS TRACTOR.  I THEN INSTRUCTED HIM TO SEE THE OFFICER ON DUTY AT THE BORDER, FOR THE PURPOSE OF CALLING 911 TO GET MEDICAL ATTENTION AND THEN TO FIND OUT WHERE HE COULD SAFELY PARK THE TRUCK.  AFTER THIS PROCESS WAS COMPLETED HE WAS TO CALL ME BACK.  I PROCEEDED TO THE OFFICE AND ARRIVED AT 4:12AM. I TELEPHONED THE FOLLOWING:  DICK ENTHORNE, (WITCO - FRIENDLY, WV), OFFICER BLANCHARD AT NRC (REPORT #426506), EPA CENTRAL OFFICE IN NEW JERSEY (JOE).  THE DRIVER CALLED BACK WHILE I WAS SPEAKING TO THE CUSTOMER.  HE STATED THE BUFFALO FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM WAS ON SITE.  I INSTRUCTED HIM TO LET THEM BREAK THE SEAL AND TO ASSURE THEY WERE PROPERLY DRESSED IN PROTECTIVE CLOTHING, GO INTO THE TRAILER AND DETERMINE WHAT WAS WRONG.  I AGAIN URGED HIM TO SEEK MEDICAL CARE FOR HIS EYES.  AS OF 5:00 AM, NO UPDATED CALLS WERE RECEIVED, SO I CALLED AND SPOKE AGAIN TO DICK ENTHORNE. THE DRIVER CALLED IN AT APPROXIMATELY 5:20 AM, STATING THE BRIDGE WAS CLOSED DUE TO POTENTIAL CATASTROPHY.  AT 5:45 AM, DICK ENTHORNE TOLD ME HE CONTACTED STEVE MCMAHON, WITCO'S ENVIRONMENTALIST. STEVE GATHERED HIS CREW OF HAZMAT EMERGENCY PROFESSIONALS AND DROVE THE WITCO CORP. HAZMAT RESPONSE VEHICLE TO THE SCENE.  AT 7:00AM, I WAS CALLED AND WAS ASKED TO PERMIT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO DRIVE OUR VEHICLE TO A SAVE HAVEN, AS THE DRIVER WAS NOW IN THE HOSPITAL. THE DRAIN HOLES WERE PLUGGED, SO PERMISSION WAS GRANTED.  WITCO'S TEAM ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30PM.  AT 4:45PM, I RECEIVED A CALL FROM STEVE MCMAHON, STATING THE AREA WAS IN THE PROCESS OF BEING SECURED, AND THAT THE POTENTIAL DANGER TO THE PUBLIC WAS ABOUT CLEARED UP.  HE STATED THEY DETERMINED THAT BOLTS WERE MISSING FROM THE PRODUCT PACKAGING, THUS CREATING THE LEAK.  EVENTUALLY, WHEN THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETE, AND THE DRIVER WAS RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL, THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE PLANT FOR THE CLEANING PROCESS TO BE COMPLETED AND TO SECURE THE CARGO FROM ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2340 HOURS MARCH 12, 1998, GETX 3004 EMPTY TANK CAR IN TRACK #34 MADISON FACILITY OF THE TERMINAL RAILROAD ASSOCIATIONS OF ST LOUIS, WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP IN A DROPLET FORM. THE UNLOADING BALL VALVE HANDLE WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION AND BOTH LOCKING PINS WERE DEFECTIVE.  BALL VALVE HANDLE WAS PLACED IN THE CLOSED POSITION AND LOCKING PIN SECURED. INSPECTION OF BOTTOM OUTLET CAP REVEALED IT TO BE HAND TIGHTENED ABOVE SECURED THE CAR.  CHEM-TREK NOTIFIED 0140 HRS 3/13/98; IL, ESDA NOTIFIED AT 0150 HRS STATE INCIDENT #980553 ASSIGNED TO REPORT.  CHEM-TREK REPRESENTING TEXACO CALLED IN RESPONSE TO NOTIFICATION BY CHEM TREK 0210 JEFF CLOSE REPRESENTATIVE OF TEXACO CALLED IN RESPONSE TO REPORT 0230 HRS.

ON SUNDAY, MARCH 16, A VERMONT AGENCY OF TRANSPORTATION PLOW TRUCK WAS REFUELING A SADDLE TANK WITH DIESEL FUEL AT ITS BASE ON THE CREEK ROAD IN MIDDLEBURY, VERMONT.  THE DRIVER LEFT THE NOZZLE UNATTENDED WHICH RESULTED IN A 20-30 GALLON OVERFILL BEFORE IT WAS DISCOVERED.  THE OVERFILL WAS REPORTED TO THE GENERAL FOREMAN OF THE DISTRICT IN COLHESTER, VERMONT ON MARCH 17 AS A "THREE TO FIVE" GALLON OVERFILL, WHICH HAD BEEN ABSORBED WITH A YARD OF SAND.  I WAS NOTIFIED THAT EVENING AND INSPECTED THE INCIDENT ON MARCH 18.  THE AREA AROUND THE FUEL PUMP, WHICH WAS PAVED, WAS STAINED.  I FOLLOWED THE STAINING ACROSS THE YARD, ACROSS A LAWN, INTO A DITCH LATERAL TO THE CREEK ROAD, TO A CULVERT WHICH ENTERED A DITCH THAT ENTERS THE OTTER CREEK.  THE RIVER HAD A LIGHT SHEEN, WHICH REACHED TWENTY FEET FROM SHORE BEFORE DISSIPATING. WITH THE USE OF PADS AND BOOMS, THE SHEEN WAS CONTAINED.  IN ADDITION, PADS WERE PLACED AT THE INLET OF THE EIGHTEEN INCH DIAMETER CULVERT.  ALL PETROLEUM CONTAMINATED SOIL ( ABOUT 10 C. Y.) WAS REMOVED AND POLYENCAPSULATED ON SITE.  HNU READINGS WERE TAKEN AND RANGED FROM 2-50 PPM WITH AN AVERAGE OF TWENTY.  BOOMS AND PADS WILL BE MONITORED DAILY AND REPLACED AS REQUIRED.  THE AGENCY POLICIES ON FUELING AND SPILL REPORTING WERE BOTH VIOLATED AND DISCIPLINARY MEASURES WILL BE TAKEN.  ADDITIONAL ENVIRONMENTAL TRAINING WILL BE GIVEN TO MAINTENANCE DIVISION SUPERVISORS.  THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER TO OFFICER FLETCHER AND THE REPORT NUMBER IS 428753.

column168: ON 3/18/97 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177, THE LOCATION WAS OUR "B" RAMP FACILITY. PART TIME, SPILL TECHNICIANS, MATTHEW GROSVENOR AND CAROLYN CORDREY RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY DISCOVERED A CARGO UNIT LOAD DEVICE EMITTING AN ODOR. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION THEY DISCOVERED THIS TO CONTAIN A FIBERBOARD BOX UPSIDE DOWN IN THE CONTAINER. THE BOX APPEARED TO BE LEAKING. A FURTHER INSPECTION FOUND THAT THE BOX HAD NO MARKINGS ON THE OUTER BOX, CONTAINER. THE BOX APPEARED TO BE LEAKING, A FURTHER INSPECTION FOUND THAT THE BOX HAD NO MARKINGS ON THE OUTER BOX, HOWEVER ATTACHED TO THE BOX WAS THE PROPER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS INDICATING THIS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL, THE INNER BOX CONTAINED 2 GLASS RECEPTACLES AT .24 LITRES EACH. THERE WERE NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES AND NO ABSORBENT WAS USED. 1 GLASS RECEPTACLE APPEARED TO HAVE LOST APPROXIMATELY .24 LITRES OF PRODUCT. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THE SHIPMENT LEAKING WAS THE IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING OF THE SHIPMENT IN  THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE. THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO THE DESTINATION.

ON 3/6/98 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. THE LOCATION WAS OUR "A" BUILDING,  SORT FACILITY, UPON INSPECTION OF THE OUTER BOX IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BOX WAS EMITTING AN ODOR, THERE WERE ALSO NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS TO INDICATE THIS TO BE A REGULATED MATERIAL. THE ONLY OUTER MARKINGS WERE THE MANUFACTURE SEAL, (LIAN HER PAPER CONTAINERS CO., LTD). UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN 4 METAL RECEPTACLES @ 2 QUARTS EACH WITH NO LABELS AND 1 PC X @ 2 QUARTS, MARKED (THINNER),  ALSO FOUND WAS 4 BOXS @ 4 X 4 OZ, IN PLASTIC BOTTLES, 16 OZ IN EACH BOX. THIS SHIPMENT WAS LEAKING AND EMITTING AN ODOR. THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND IS BEING HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS CLOSURE FAILURE DUE TO NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE CLOSURE.

column168: MGR CTS R SLOANE WAS NOTIFIED OF TWELVE CAR DERAILMENT AT CLAGSTONE, ID. TANK CAR CITX 35086 WAS REPORTED TO BE "HISSING" FROM THE "DOME"  MGR SLOANE ADVISED THAT AT 100 FOOT RADIUS PERIMETER AROUND THE CAR SHOULD BE ISOLATED UNTIL HE COULD INSPECT THE CAR. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DERAILMENT SITE MGR SLOANE & MGR MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, RICHARD BIELSMITH DISCUSSED THE SAFETY PRECAUTIONS FOR THE SITE AND THEN MGR SLOANE INSPECTED THE TANK CAR.  THE CAR WAS ON ITS "R" SIDE AT 90 DEG THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS OPEN AND THERE WAS AN AUDIBLE HISS COMING FROM ONE OF THE FITTINGS.  MR SLOANE DETERMINED THE HISS WAS COMING FROM THE "A" END LIQUID LINE VALVE AT THE PLUG.  HE CLOSED THE VALVE AND TIGHTENED THE PLUG WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  MGR SLOANE CHECKED THE REMAINING VALVES AND FOUND ALL HAD PLUGS LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  HE PROPERLY SECURED ALL FITTINGS.

column168: AT 730 AM ON 030798, GEOFFREY REEDER, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, RECEIVED A REPORT OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AT ENGLEWOOD YARD.  UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER OBSERVED A BLOCK OF ICE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR ABOUT ONE FOOT THICK.  LIQUID ARGON WAS DRIPPING FROM THE CUBE OF ICE.  REEDER ASKED THAT THE CART BE ISOLATED.  UPON ARRIVAL OF A SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE, THE ICE WAS CHIPPED AWAY AND A SMALL VALVE FOUND OPEN.  THERE WAS NO PLUG IN THE VALVE (OTHER PRODUCT VALVES ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR ALSO DID NOT HAVE PLUGS).  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE LIQUID LEAK STOPPED.  THE RUPTURE DISC ON THE LEFT SIDE HAD ALSO FAILED.  PRAXAIR OBTAINED A NEW DISC FROM THEIR PLANT AND INSTALLED IT. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT.

column168: ON MARCH 17 AT APPROXIMATELY 4PM MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, GEOGGREY REEDER, RECEIVED A REPORT OF A LEAKING TANK CART AT ANGLETON, TX. CAR FOREMAN LONNIE MUSE NOTED A STREAM OF LIQUID COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE  CAR. MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, BILL STREELY NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, DOW CHEMICAL, AND ASKED THAT THEY SEND THEIR RESPONSE TEAM.  DOW TEAM  LEADER DENNIS WOOSTER INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOND THE FOUR BOLTS HOLDING THE BLIND FLANGE ON THE LIQUID VALVE WERE LOOSE. ONE OF THE BOLTS WAS SO CORRODED IT COULD NOT BE REUSED AND WAS REPLACED.  THE REMAINING BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED.  THE DOW TEAM RINSED THE CAR WITH A LIME SOLUTION TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID.

SEAL FC TX 137560 WAS REMOVED FROM THE VALVE COVER AND UPB 203033 WAS APPLIED.  GREG, RMCC, WAS ADVISED.  HE NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND REGIONAL MANAGER HERBY BART.

column168: THE BOX WAS BEING LOADED INTO THE TRUCK WHEN THE INNER CONTENTS SHIFTED, CAUSING ALL 200 ROUNDS TO DISCHARGE.  THAT MANIFESTED IN A LOUD "POP" FROM THE BOX.  THEN A PUFF OF SMOKE, FOLLOWED BY A STRONG ODOR OF SULFUR.  THE FEDEX EMPLOYEE SET THE BOX ON THE GROUND, RETREATED, AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL UNIT, AND BOMB SQUAD WERE NOTIFIED.  THE BOX WAS REMOVED (EVENTUALLY) FROM THE STATION AND OPENED.  WHEN THE BOX WAS OPENED WE FOUND THAT ALL 200 ROUNDS HAD BEEN DISCHARGED, AND THERE WAS CHARRING IN THE BOX.  IT APPEARED THAT THE 200 ROUNDS WERE SERATED BY 2 SHOT PUTS. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE SHOT PUTS SHIFTED CAUSING THE DISCHARGE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT.  I NOTIFIED THE FAA AND SPOKE TO SPECIAL AGENT JOE BALLAS WITH THE NEWARK CASFO. THE FREIGHT WAS BEEN INSPECTED BY THE FAA THIS MORNING.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS THAT WOULD HAVE READILY ALLOWED US TO IDENTIFY THE CONTENTS AS BEING REGULATED BY THE US DOT.

ON 3/24/98 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177. THE LOCATION WAS OUR "C" BUILDING, SORT FACILITY, SPILL TECHNICIANS, MARTIN  CLINE AND BRUCE SHILTZ RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DISCOVERED A PLASTIC EXPRESS PACKAGE EMITTING AN ODOR.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE ENVELOPE, IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS TO INDICATE THIS TO BE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THEY FOUND 1 X T SHIRT AND 1 BROKEN GLASS RECEPTACLE CONTAINING WOOD TOUCH UP.  ALL OF THE WOOD TOUCH WAS LOST, THIS PRODUCT WAS BELIEVED TO BE FLAMMABLE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND IS BEING HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING WAS POSSIBLE DAMAGE BY OTHER FREIGHT.

ABOUT 3OZ OF LIQIUD FROM THE VALVE, MIKR PATERNOSTER PLACED SPEEDY DRY AROUND THE VALVE AND TIGHTEN THE VALVE TO AVOID SPILLAGE. THE LID CAME OFF OF A 16 GAL DRUM WHILE IT WAS BEING PICKED UP OFF OF THE DOCK TO GO ONTO TRUCK SK5143.  THE SPILL WAS ON THE TRUCK AND ON CONCRETE (NO OPEN DRAINS).  THE SPILL WAS RECOVERED WITH ABSORBENT AND EVERYTHING WAS DRUMMED UP (100% RECOVERY).  THE CUSTOMER IS SATISFIED.  THE CUSTOMER CONTACT IS UNKNOWN.

THE SHIPPER DUPONT MERCK (BOSTON MA.) OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL BY MR. PAUL O'DONNELL (LOS ANGELES COUNTY FIRE EMERGENCY HAZMAT) AT 1845 ON 3-3-98. DUPONT MERCK (BOSTON, MA) CONTACTED MR. GARY STAGGS, DISTRIBUTION MANAGER DUPONT MERCK, (TORRANCE CA). MR. STAGGS RESPONDED BY COMING TO THE LOS ANGELES INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT. MR. STAGGS NOTIFIED DELTA AIR LINES AT APPROXIMATELY 2300. THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT HANDLED THE CLEAN UP. THE AREA WAS CHECKED WITH A GIEGERCOUNTER BY MR. STAGGS AND THE L.A. COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT WASHED DOWN THE AREA. THE LOS ANGELES DEPARTMENT OF AIRPORTS CLEARED A TWENTY FOOT PERIMETER AROUND TWO SPILL SITES. AT APPROXIMATELY 2123 THE LAX DOA RE-OPENED THE SOUTH EAST PORTION OF THE SERVICE ROAD BETWEEN RUNWAYS 25L AND 25R. IT APPEARS AT THIS TIME THAT THE TWO BOXES OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL FELL OUT OF A CART WHILE IN TRANSIT FROM THE DELTA AIR LINES CARGO FACILITY TO THE DELTA  AIR LINES TERMINAL. THE TWO BOXES WERE CRUSHED BY AN UNKNOWN VEHICLE. TWO OF THE VIALS OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL WERE COMPROMISED AND THE CONTENTS SPILLED ON TO A SERVICE ROAD AT THE LOS ANGELES INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT. THE TIME OF THE ACTUAL SPILL IS ESTIMATED TO BE APPROXIMATELY 1440 BASED ON THE TIME THE SHIPMENT DEPARTED THE DELTA AIR LINES CARGO FACILITY. ACCORDING TO THE LOS ANGELES DEPARTMENT OF THE AIRPORT POLICE, THE FIRST REPORT OF THE DANGEROUS GOODS SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE DEPARTMENT OF AIRPORT POLICE AT 1526. THIS REPORT CAME FROM THE LOS ANGELES DEPARTMENT OF AIRPORT OPERATIONS UNIT 60. AT 1542 LOS ANGELES AIRPORT POLICE NOTIFIED THE LOS ANGELES FIRE DEPARTMENT AT 1542. ACCORDING TO THE LOS ANGELES DEPARTMENT OF AIRPORT POLICE, THE SPILL WAS CLEARED AT 2123. THIS PER LAX D.O.A. POLICE COMMUNICATIONS OPERATOR 113. SPECIAL AGENT FRANK L. WEBB WITH THE U.S. DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AT 10:45 PST ON 3-4-98. A VERBAL REPORT WAS TAKEN FROM DELTA AIR LINES TEAM LEADER, ROBERT FULLER. MR. WEBB WORKS OUT OF THE: LAX-CIVIL AVIATION SECURITY FIELD OFFICE 5757 W. CENTURY BLVD. SUITE 500 LOS ANGELES, CA 90045. ADDITIONAL INFORMATION: DURING THE TIME IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING THE REPORT OF THE INCIDENT, THE SERVICE ROAD BETWEEN RUNWAYS 25L AND 25R REMAINED CLOSED TO VEHICLE TRAFFIC. THERE WAS NO CLOSURE OF ANY ACTIVE RUNWAYS OR TAXI WAYS. POST NUMBER FOUR WAS ALSO CLOSED TO TRAFFIC FOR VEHICLE ON AND OFF THE A.O.A.

column168: AT 17:00 HOUR ON 3/10/98, A ALLWASTE ENVIROMENTAL SERVICES, A PHILIP SERVICES CORPORATION COMPANY VACUUM TRUCK EXPERIENCED HYDRAULIC FAILURE IN THE END CLOSURE AREA.  A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 5 NEAR THE EXIT TO 516/KENT.  THE SPILL WAS APPROXIMATELY 1/4 TO 1/2 MILE IN LENGTH BY 2 INCHES WIDE ON THE INTERSTATE ROADWAY AND AN AREA 3 FEET BY 40 FEET ON THE SHOULDER OF THE INTERSTATE.  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE, CHRIS MASTERS, WAS CONTACTED BY WASHINGTON STATE PATROL.   THE DRIVER THEN CONTACTED JOHN WILES, OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR, OF ALLWASTE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, A PHILIP SERVICES COMPANY, CONCERNING THE RELEASE OF MATERIAL.  JOHN WILES ARRIVED AT THE SCENE OF THE INCIDENT SHORTLY THERE AFTER.  JOHN WILES THEN SPOKE TO THE WASHINGTON DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY CONCERNING THE RELEASE OF MATERIALS.  JOHN WILES WAS GIVEN SPECIFICATIONS FROM THE DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY CONCERNING THE CLEAN UP AND REMOVAL OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS SECURED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO BURLINGTON ENVIRONMENTAL INC.,  A PHILIP SERVICES CORPORATION COMPANY, AT 20245 77TH AVE., SOUTH KENT, WA. 98032.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS THEN ABSORBED WITH FLOOR DRY, COLLECTED, AND PLACED WITHIN DRUMS FOR TRANSPORT TO BURLINGTON ENVIRONMENTAL INC., A PHILIP SERVICES CORPORATION COMPANY, AT 20245 77TH AVE., S KENT, WA 98032.  THE MATERIAL WAS MANAGED AT THE KENT FACILITY OF BURLINGTON ENVIRONMENTAL INC., A PHILIP SERVICES CORPORATION COMPANY, FOR FINAL DISPOSAL.  JOHN WILES THEN CONTACTED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AT 0800 ON 3/11/98 AND CASE NUMBER 427774A3 WAS ASSIGNED.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY THE DENVER RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN YERMO, CALIFORNIA.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED FRANK VALDEZ, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, WHO ADVISED THE WEST SWITCH JOB HAD OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE TOP AREA OF THE CAR DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  AS THE CAR WAS PLACARDED CORROSIVE, IT WAS ISOLATED ON THE CABOOSE TRACK, PENDING AN INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TOT HE YERMO YARD AND UPON INSPECTING THE TANK, FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT.  TE SAFETY VENT, MOUNTED OUTSIDE THE WORK PLATFORM AREA ON THE 'A' END OF THE CAR, A STANDARD GATX TRIVENT ASSEMBLY, WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 165 POUND ZOOK DISC.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED, AND FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED.  AS THE CAR WAS NOT OVERLOADED, IT APPEARS IT HAD BEEN ROUGH HANDLED DURING TRANSIT, CAUSING A LIQUID SURGE WITHIN THE CAR THAT BLEW OUT THE FRANGIBLE DISC.  DUE TO THE TYPE AND MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WRE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION.
